The previous owner assures me that it fires and operates just fine.This shotgun does have a magazine plug installed. I only had 2 1/2 shells handy, and I could fit two in the magazine. title: For Sale:  Argentine Sist. Colt Cal. 11.25mm Mod 1927 (45acp)
postcontent:
Argentine Sist. Colt Cal. 11.25mm Mod 1927 (45acp), numbers matching, except magazine , older aftermarket grips, made in 1960, Argentine Government Crest on slide,

In 1943, the Argentine Military Small Arms Factory (FMAP - Fabrica Militar de Armas Portatiles) began to prepare for the manufacture of Model 1927 pistols under the 1927 licensing agreement. These pistols were known as "Pistola Sistema "Colt" Modelo Argentino 1927, Calibre 11,25mm." Production began at the Esteban de Luca Arsenal in Buenos Aires, with the first pistols actually being assembled at the Domingo Matheu plant in Rosario, Argentina in 1945. The pistols were manufactured in accordance with Colt's 1927 drawings. They were exact copies of Colt's 1927 pistols (identical to US military M1911A1 pistols) except for very minor differences, and parts were interchangeable. The only noticeable differences were the markings, grips, black oxide bluing, a sharp edge on the rear of the hammer, and a sharp edge on the heel of the grip safety. Triggers were solid as on the 1927 Colts , and the checkering on the mainspring housing was changed from Colt type cut checkering to indented checkering.
The Sistema Colt pistols were made for the army, navy, air force, government bureaus, police organizations, and commercial sales. They were normally serial numbered on the right side of the receiver, the grip frame under the mainspring housing, on the top and right side of the slide, on the top of the chamber and the bottom of the magazine. The presence of an Argentine crest on the pistol indicates government issue; pistols without crests were made for local police, non-government agencies, commercial sales and export. All Sistema Colt pistols bear the marking D.G.F.M. - (F.M.A.P.) on the left side of the slide, which indicates manufacture by the Direccion General de Fabricaciones Militares at the Fabrica Militar de Armas Portatiles. A total of 88,494 Sistema Colt pistols were produced.
$600 OBO

title: For Sale/Trade:  WWII Remington Model 1903A3 – Beautiful!
location: Stillwater or St. Paul, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
This particular rifle is from a good friends Dad.  Dad brought the rifle back with him after the war (no perceived story of “a bring back”, the honest truth). The rifle barrel is marked RA, ordnance bomb, 11-43.  The serial number is 4107083.  The wood inspection stamps, cartouches and proof marks are all crisp. It is all original and in outstanding condition.  The wood and metal are superb. Only the smallest of handling marks on the wood that I had to look hard to find.  The metal is in as issued, like new condition. The follower does not have any scrapes or scratches, thus I am not sure it has ever had a round loaded in it or even been shot.  This is a $1200-$1500 rifle by anyone’s estimate.

BUT!!!  When Dad brought it home, he wanted to make it into a deer rifle.  So he had the receiver drilled and tapped and put scope mounts on it.  Then, he grinded off part of the bolt handle so a scope would have clearance.  I know, I know …..  but remember back then there were thousands of these around so they were not special, even in outstanding condition. While Dad had the scope mounts installed, he never put a scope on it and never took it hunting.  He never even shot it.  So it has been sitting in his (or his son’s) closet for the last 70 years. Dad is in his last stages of life and his son does not want it.  That is why I am helping him find a home for it with someone who will appreciate the history of this fine rifle.

This rifle could be used in many ways.  Mount a modern scope on it and it would be the coolest hunting rifle on the range….. replace the bolt and scope mounts with the original bolt, scope mounts and scope from the war years…… replace the bolt with and original, put on an original rear sight (which would cover the rear scope mount hole) and fill the holes on the front of the receiver and return it to its as manufactured condition…… or just keep it as it is with a great story and a great piece of personal and war history.

I have many more pictures, just email me to request.... it is in excellent condition!

title: For Sale:  NIB High Standard M-101 w/ threaded barrel prototype
postcontent:
NIB / Unfired High Standard M-101 Dura-Matic. 1980s manufacture date. 4 1/2 inch barrel in S/N matching box with the papers and goodies from the factory (registration, safety papers, “packed by” label, etc.). Although this one is unfired, I’ve had several and they are remarkably accurate and solid shooters. The slide feels like it’s on ball bearings and the handgun is typical Hi-Standard: as in “heavy.”



What sets this one apart, besides the fact that it’s never been fired? Included is an extra barrel: 6-inches, professionally machined and modified to accept a muzzle brake or suppressor. This extra barrel is also in factory-new condition and the story passed down was that it was a “factory prototype”. Sounds far-fetched, except for one thing: the threaded socket which accepts the M-101s thumbscrew needs to be tapped about 1 – 2 more threads to snugly tighten down onto the frame of the handgun. Seems like a simple task, but I’ve chosen, over the years, to leave it alone because that one “flaw” attests to the authenticity of the story. 

Either of these two items would be unusual by itself. Together, they are a rare and interesting combination.

Handgun is in 10/10 condition. No marks. No wear. Ditto the extra barrel. Bluing is perfect except for the machined areas on the extra barrel. See pics. Again, it would have been simple to have it blued by a gunsmith but precision of the machining is evidenced by which areas are blued and which areas are not. 

Comes with 2 authentic (not aftermarket) High Standard 10-rd magazines, which show some minor wear from hand-loading, but otherwise appear to be brand new and unused. The outside of the box shows some wear, but S/N is intact.

title: For Sale:  1924 Transition 1911
postcontent:
Pre-WWII Colt 1911 U.S. ARMY .45 automatic. This pistol was produced in 1924 and remains in excellent condition. This is one of 10,000 "transition" pistols that were manufactured in 1924. While still marked "1911", these pistols had the new improvements that would eventually cause the pistol to be renamed "1911A1". This is one of the early transition pistols with the WTG monogram enclosed within a single circle formed by his initial G. Roughly 2000 pistols were marked in this manner and this is a very hard variation for the collector to locate.

he seriffed "H" proofs are properly matching on both the slide and frame. The intertwined HP barrel is also of the correct type and has the proper “K” stamping on the bottom. The barrel itself appears to have been refinished and the crown at the muzzle is more flattened than usual. The pistol wears a very nice set of 28 row full checkered walnut grips that were issued as one the transitional changes. This fine single circled monogram piece of history was shipped February 7, 1924 in a shipment of 1000 to the Commanding officer of Springfield Armory.

5500 Firm in the Houston area.  Can send more photos upon request.
